Now this is going to make a function that shows the correlation coefficient on the lower panel, and the scatter plots on the upper panel

X<-cbind(newPb100k_dec,newAge,newPb_elev,newAvg_km,newTeique_sf,newSteu_b,newStem_b)
panel.cor<-function(x,y,digits=2,prefix="", cex.cor, ...) {
  usr<-par("usr");on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr=c(0,1,0,1))
  r<-cor(x,y)
  txt<-format(c(r,0.123456789),digits=digits)[1]
  txt<-paste0(prefix,txt)
  if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor<-0.8/strwidth(txt)
  text(0.5,0.5,txt,cex=cex.cor*r)
}
pairs(newPb100k_dec~newAge+newPb_surface+ newPb_elev+newAvg_km+newTeique_sf+newSteu_b+newStem_b,lower.panel=panel.cor)

Based on our Box-cox methods, it’s evident that we will need to adjust our Age variable, Pb_elev and Pb100k_dec to create a better model

transformedAge = log(newAge)
transformedPb_surface = (newPb_surface^(-3.56)-1)/(-3.56)
transformedPb_elv = newPb_elev^(1/2)
transformedPb100k_dec = log(newPb100k_dec)
transformedStem_b = newStem_b^2

Using these transformed variables, we will now create a new model using these variables.

m2=lm(transformedPb100k_dec~transformedAge+newSex+transformedPb_surface +transformedPb_elv+ newAvg_km+newTeique_sf+newSteu_b+newStem_b)
